# Multi-Model Routing

**Applies when:** the kit is configured in `multi-model` mode (set by `ai-resources setup`).

## Architecture

```
Cockpit (Claude Code / Cursor / Gemini CLI / etc.)
    │  ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:4000
    ▼
LiteLLM gateway (local container or remote)
    │  inspects {"model": "..."} field
    ▼
Provider (Anthropic / Google / OpenAI / Vertex / Ollama)
```

The cockpit's HTTP calls hit LiteLLM at the configured `gateway.url` (default
`127.0.0.1:4000`). LiteLLM reads the `model` field from each request and
routes to the matching provider, translating between API formats as needed.

## Single source of truth: `~/.config/ai-resources/executors.yaml`

```yaml
version: 1
profile_name: unified-default
gateway:
  url: http://127.0.0.1:4000
  api_key_env: LITELLM_MASTER_KEY
by_role:
  research:           { provider: google,    model: gemini-2.5-pro }
  planner:            { provider: anthropic, model: claude-sonnet-4-6 }
  software-architect: { provider: anthropic, model: claude-opus-4-7 }
  implementer:        { provider: anthropic, model: claude-sonnet-4-6 }
  ...
```

Each role's `model` value is sent **verbatim** to the gateway. To change which
model runs a role, edit this file and re-run `ai-resources setup` (or run
`ai-resources daemon restart` if only the gateway config changed).

## How subagents inherit models

In Claude Code, subagent files at `~/.claude/agents/<role>.md` declare:

```yaml
---
name: research
description: ...
model: gemini-2.5-pro      # ← string passes through to gateway
tools: Read, Grep, Glob
---
```

The `model:` value is **not validated** by Claude Code against an Anthropic
allowlist (verified empirically). Any string the gateway recognizes works:
`claude-sonnet-4-6`, `gemini-2.5-pro`, `gpt-5`, `vertex_ai/claude-sonnet-...`,
etc.

For other cockpits (Cursor, Aider, etc.), the equivalent assignment lives in
their own config (e.g. Aider's `architect-model` / `model` / `weak-model`).

## What works cross-provider

- ✅ **Tools** (Read, Write, Bash, Grep, Edit) — Claude Code executes locally;
  only the model's tool-use call format is translated by LiteLLM.
- ✅ **MCP servers** (Engram, etc.) — appear as standard tools to the model;
  format-translated by LiteLLM.
- ✅ **Skills** — text injected into context; agnostic to provider.
- ✅ **Workspace access** — same as native Claude Code.
- ✅ **Workflow YAML iteration** — orchestrator behavior unchanged.

## What does NOT work cross-provider

- ❌ **Anthropic prompt caching** — `cache_control` headers are Anthropic-only.
  When routing to Gemini/OpenAI, caching is lost (Gemini and OpenAI have their
  own caching, format-specific).
- ❌ **Anthropic-only beta features** — computer-use, code-execution betas,
  citations. Use Claude models for subagents that depend on these.
- ⚠️ **Edge-case translation** — parallel tool calls, complex JSON Schema
  with refs/oneOf, streaming + tools may have variance. Most basic flows work.

## Single source for cost / observability

LiteLLM logs every call. Use:

- `ai-resources daemon logs` — raw logs
- `ai-resources audit` — cost breakdown per role/model
- `ai-resources executors test <role>` — round-trip a single role

## When mode is `single-model`

Multi-model routing is bypassed. The cockpit talks directly to its native
provider (e.g. Claude Code → Anthropic). `executors.yaml` is not used. The
legacy `model:` mapping (`strong`/`fast`/`inherit` → opus/haiku/inherit) still
applies for subagent files.

## Health check

Run `ai-resources doctor` to verify:
- LiteLLM gateway is reachable
- Each configured model accepts a tiny round-trip
- All credentials are loaded
- Cockpits are configured

## Relation to other rules

- `010-orchestrator.mdc` — workflow iteration is unchanged; only the model
  behind each subagent changes.
- `050-subagent-delegation.mdc` — subagent dispatch is unchanged; the
  Task tool still spawns subagents; their `model:` is multi-provider-aware.
- `200-security-mcp.mdc` — credentials in `~/.config/ai-resources/.env`
  (chmod 600); never committed; `${env:VAR}` references in YAML.
